The number one question I get asked… “How do I get into Aviation Photography“
This question was asked during my latest “ask me anything” and I felt that I needed to expand on this answer since I get asked it so often.
Quality begets further quality. In this case it's a combination of John "Slick" Baum's Cafe X IWC Pilot's Bag, Big Pilot's Watch, and his 1944 Boeing Stearman.
Reminiscing of this classic sortie from Osh ‘22.

My portrait of Terence Ford (@terenceford) - Photographer, Director, Instructor, Actor…he’s done it all. 

A commercial photographer who also established the fStop Warrior Project - a non-profit organization in the form of a photography class that helps military veterans. 

He was assistant Director to Ridley Scott on Blade Runner and Outbreak, assistant director on 400+ commercials, has acted in a variety of movies and tv, and the impressive list goes on. 

His wit is unmatched and will always have you laughing. It was great to get in the studio with him.

Also, I owe him a watch.

Pilot John “Slick” Baum tested and approved. 

Made of military specified nylon oxford, the WEP USN/USMC Bomber Jacket was a favorite among the fighter pilots of the U.S. Navy and the United States Marine Corps during the 1950s, 60s and 70s. 

Today, this jacket can be styled casually with a pair of jeans for a night out in the city… or at least that’s how former USAF Thunderbird Pilot and USAF Weapons School graduate and instructor John “Slick” Baum likes to wear it!
Definitely a ‘style we fly with’ ✈️

If you caught our episode on the @smithsonian_channel and were wondering what gear I was using - The @canonusa R5 C is a true hybrid camera and is a game changer for me by being able to seamlessly switch from stills to video up to 8K/60P Internal RAW. 

This is a big deal for me because I am photographing and filming with the doors off so I need to limit the amount of gear I have with me. Plus I have my Gyro stabilizer fixed to the bottom of the camera so it allows me to keep it on one camera while getting two jobs done.

I was a kid when I first picked up my dad’s 35mm camera, and I’ve been obsessed ever since. I always took photography classes in high school and a cinematography class my senior year. 

However, it took me several years of working jobs I hated to finally try to make a career out of photography. And thanks to a wild fire that burned all of my belongings, insurance cut me a check, so I headed straight to the photography store and stocked up on gear. 

I started working with a few photographers to get my feet wet, and worked for a few magazines shooting editorials at the same time. 

After a few years I really wanted to change things up and grow, so I moved to Santa Barbara to attend Brooks Institute of Photography. Afterwards I continued freelancing for several years - mostly photographing people (athletes, musicians, actors, models) and then action sports. 

Then, while filming an off-road racing team, I was introduced to the owner of @lewisairlegends, Rod Lewis. His trust in me led to photographing his collection of aircraft, which gave me a sizable aviation portfolio - I’m forever grateful for his trust. 

Several years later, I’ve been fortunate enough to photograph some amazing aircraft over beautiful landscapes, work with brands I’ve admired, and met some truly stellar people along the way that also helped me get where I am today. And I’m proud to say that @canonusa has been in my hand through my entire photographic journey. 

And finally a HUGE thank you to my brother for introducing me to photography as a kid, my mom and dad for their encouragement to pursue photography professionally, and my wife for being my biggest advocate and helping me through this wild career. 

That’s it. Have a great day ✌️
